## Mandatory Validation After Every Change

Every modification to Supabase-related code MUST pass these checks:

### 1. Column Audit
For every Supabase `.insert()`, `.upsert()`, `.update()`:
- Cross-reference EVERY column name against `supabase/schema.sql`
- Verify column types match (string→TEXT, number→INTEGER/NUMERIC, object→JSONB, array→JSONB)
- Verify NOT NULL columns have fallback values
- Verify FK columns reference valid IDs (UUIDs, not localStorage timestamp IDs)

### 2. Read Mapping Audit
For every Supabase `.select()`:
- Verify snake_case→camelCase mapping matches the TypeScript interface
- Verify JSONB fields are properly typed/cast
- Verify null fallbacks for optional columns

### 3. Delete Sync Audit
When items can be removed from the app:
- Verify corresponding DELETE logic exists in `pushToSupabase` or the relevant function
- Never leave orphaned rows in Supabase

### 4. TypeScript Verification
```
npx tsc --noEmit    # Must pass with ZERO errors
```

### 5. Lint Check
Use ReadLints on all modified files — must have zero new errors.

### 6. Unique Constraint Audit
For every `.upsert()`:
- Verify `onConflict` column(s) match the actual UNIQUE constraint in schema.sql
- Example: `training_insights` has `UNIQUE(group_id, player_name)` → `onConflict: 'group_id,player_name'`

## Key Architecture Decisions

### Feature Flag Pattern
```typescript
if (USE_SUPABASE) {
  // Supabase path — direct DB operations
  const gid = getGroupId();
  if (!gid) return fallback;
  // ... supabase operations
  return result;
}
// Legacy path — unchanged
```

### Cache-as-localStorage Pattern
`supabaseCache.ts` presents a synchronous localStorage-like interface to all existing code. Writes are debounced and pushed to Supabase asynchronously. This avoids refactoring all 76+ storage functions.

### ID Strategy
- Legacy: timestamp-based string IDs (e.g., `"1709234567890"`)
- Supabase: UUID v4 (e.g., `"a1b2c3d4-e5f6-..."`)
- `storage.ts` generates UUIDs when `USE_SUPABASE = true`
- Migration script (`migrateToSupabase.ts`) maps old IDs → new UUIDs via `IdMap`

### Multi-Tenancy
Every table has `group_id` column. RLS policies enforce `group_id` matches the user's group. `getGroupId()` from `supabaseCache.ts` provides the current group.

## Group Management SQL RPCs (`supabase/004-group-management.sql`)

9 RPCs with owner-aware security. All sensitive operations check `groups.created_by` to distinguish owner from regular admin.

| RPC | Who Can Call | Purpose |
|-----|-------------|---------|
| `create_group(name, display_name)` | Any authenticated user | Creates group, auto-creates owner player, inserts default settings |
| `join_group_by_invite(code, display_name)` | Any authenticated user | Joins group via invite code, adds member with `member` role |
| `link_member_to_player(target_player_id)` | Any group member | Links own account to an existing player (with uniqueness check) |
| `self_create_and_link(player_name)` | Any group member | Creates new player and links self to it |
| `update_member_role(target_user_id, new_role)` | Admin (owner for admin targets) | Changes a member's role |
| `remove_group_member(target_user_id)` | Admin (owner for admin targets) | Removes a member from group |
| `transfer_ownership(new_owner_id)` | Owner only | Transfers group ownership (target must be admin) |
| `regenerate_invite_code()` | Owner only | Generates new invite code, invalidates old |
| `unlink_member_player(target_user_id)` | Admin (owner for admin targets) | Unlinks member from their player record |

### Schema Changes in `004-group-management.sql`
- `group_members.display_name TEXT` — user's display name in the group
- `settings.gemini_api_key TEXT` — per-group Gemini API key
- `settings.elevenlabs_api_key TEXT` — per-group ElevenLabs API key
- Partial unique index `idx_gm_unique_player` on `group_members(group_id, player_id) WHERE player_id IS NOT NULL`
- FK `group_members.player_id` changed to `ON DELETE SET NULL`

## API Key Flow (Supabase Mode)

```
Group owner sets keys in Settings > AI tab
  → Saved to `settings` table (gemini_api_key / elevenlabs_api_key)
  → Client reads from getSettings() via getGroupGeminiKey() / getGroupElevenLabsKey()
  → Sent in proxy request body to Vercel Edge Functions
  → Edge Function: request body key > env var fallback > error
```

This ensures each group uses its own keys. The Vercel env var serves as a global fallback (e.g., for the owner's primary group).

